observations.recommendation:
We recommended the following measures to the Local Chief Executive:
Establish an Inventory Committee to promptly perform a comprehensive physical inventory of all Property, Plant, and Equipment (PPE) of the Municipality, adhering to the guidelines and procedures detailed in COA Circular No. 2020-006, to ensure compliance with the mandated One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to prepare and submit a reliable RPCPPE in the prescribed format provided in the NGAS for LGUs;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Head of General Services Office to maintain subsidiary ledger card and property card for each PPE account, respectively, ensuring coordination and reconciliation of records are regularly undertaken to minimize, if not eliminate, any discrepancy in the reported PPE account balances; and
Conduct joint training sessions and workshops for both the GSO and Accounting Office to enhance personnel capacity in PPE management, report preparation, and proper documentation to ensure alignment and coordination for effective operations.
Consider providing additional staff with consideration to their experience, background, and education that may assist the GSO in the performance of her functions.

In view of these observations, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive of Municipality of San Fabian in compliance with COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-1 dated January 30, 2024 to:
Immediately constitute the Disposal Committee in compliance with COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-001 to facilitate the proper disposal of unserviceable properties;
Ensure coordination between the Inventory Committee and the Disposal Committee to comply with the provisions of Section A (1.5) of the circular, ensuring an effective and systematic approach to PPE management and disposal;
Initiate disposal proceedings immediately through the collaboration with the GSO Designate to avoid further deterioration of the properties and consequent depreciation of their value, if warranted; and
Require the Municipal Engineer in coordination with the Municipal Accountant to evaluate the cost-effectiveness of continued repairs on frequently serviced equipment and consider disposal or replacement when warranted.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive issue the following directives:
Conduct joint training sessions and workshops for both the GSO and Accounting Office on inventory management, report preparation, and proper documentation to ensure alignment and coordination;
Establish an Inventory Committee immediately to conduct a complete physical count of all inventoriable items and to submit a reliable RPCI to the Office of the Auditor;
Instruct the GSO-Designated to prepare the weekly SSMI based on the original RIS submitted and subsequently submit it to the Municipal Accountant;
Require Municipal Accountant to record inventory issuances as expenses based on the SSMI received from GSO-Designated;
Ensure that both the Municipal Accountant and the GSO maintain updated SLC and SC and undertake regular reconciliation between the two records; and
Require the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to implement the general process to be followed in the control of inventory as stated in Section 122- Inventory Process in NGAS Manual as shown in Annex A.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to undertake the following courses of action, to wit:
Establish claims on these receivables by reviewing the records, work back, if necessary, by gathering and reconstructing all pertinent supporting documents for valid claims, such as bills and statement of accounts;
Enforce the collection of valid accounts by sending demand letters or by withholding payments of money claims due the concerned employees and other individuals;
Issuing formal demand letters requiring immediate payment of the full amount due, to enforce the collection of Due from Officers and Employees arising from cash shortages. Otherwise, coordinate with the Office of the Solicitor General to initiate legal action against non-compliant individuals, if necessary;
Make concerted efforts to collect outstanding receivables accounts; and
Revisit and implement policies to improve the collection of receivables.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Immediately submit or provide to the Audit Team the supporting documents for further verification;
Ensure that all supporting documents are complete before preparing the JEV and recording the same. Also, attach the original supporting documents to the JEV for submission to the Audit Team, and;
All payables that cannot be supported with complete documentation should be reverted to the surplus account. The Accounts Payable and related accounts should be adjusted through correcting journal entries.

We recommended that in compliance with COA Circular No. 2018-002 dated May 31, 2018, and Republic Act No. 656 the Local Chief Executive to:
Instruct the GSO Designate to identify and prepare a list of all insurable assets of the Municipality;
Require the GSO Designate to accomplish the required Property Inventory Form (PIF) based on the list of insurable properties, for submission to the GSIS. The PIF must include details such as the latest appraised values or valuation, appraisal date, location, and other relevant information;
Direct the GSO Designate to coordinate with the GSIS to arrange insurance coverage, in compliance with Republic Act No. 656 and COA Circular No. 2018-002, and;
Request an additional budget for next year budget call to the Budget Officer to cover the payment of premiums for all identified insurable properties and ensure sufficient appropriations are included in future budgets to maintain full coverage; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to require a copy of the List of Insurable Properties submitted by the GSO Designate and closely monitor the payment of the additional Insurance premium in collaboration with the Municipal Budget Officer.

We recommended the following to the Management:

8. a. Instruct the Disposal Committee to conduct inspection, inventory and appraisal of unserviceable properties derecognized and accomplish the required Inventory and Inspection Report with their description and other required information of the property;

9. b. Submit to COA the Inventory Report of Unserviceable Properties for the inspection and approval by the COA Regional Technical Evaluation Services (RTES);

In order to improve the controls over the inventories which will result to more reliable balances in the Financial Statements, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive to:

10. a. Instruct the GSO to prepare the weekly SSMI based on the original RIS submitted by the various offices responsible in the custody of these inventories and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant;

11. b. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to recognize the issuances of inventories based from the SSMI submitted by the GSO to properly record the corresponding expenditures;

12. c. Create an Inventory Committee that shall conduct a complete physical inventory of all inventories and to submit the corresponding RPCI to the Office of the Auditor; and 

13. d. Instruct the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to maintain an updated SLC and stock cards, respectively.

We recommended that the Management:

20. a. To instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to cease from paying and issuing checks to suppliers or contractors without complete documentation;

21. b. Refrain from lending vouchers and documents to unauthorized personnel and observe properly the guidelines in the disbursement process;

22. c. Henceforth, submit regularly and completely all DVs and supporting documents to COA within the prescribed period to establish the validity, propriety and legality of the disbursements made by the LGU and to avoid penalty of the Revised Penal Code.

We recommended and Management agreed to instruct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to:

27. a. Observe strict compliance to the principle of confidentiality of procurement documents and in line with the commitment of the GOP to promote good governance and its effort to adhere to the principles of transparency, efficiency and economy in the procurement process;

28. b. Check the authenticity and completeness of canvass papers/quotations supporting shopping procurements to depict therein the names and contact number of persons attesting related quotations in the name of supplier for verification purposes;

29. c. Ensure chronology of events of procurement activities to establish propriety of transactions; and

30. d. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the documents were properly filled up and dated.

We recommended that in order to establish reasonableness of cost and obtain the most advantageous price in various procurement, Management instruct:

33. a. All departments to indicate the price per item in the PPMP which is the basis in the preparation of the APP;

34. b. All requesting departments/offices to indicate the cost of each item being requested based on the price database of the GSO to set the maximum price ceiling for each item;

35. c. The General Services office (GSO) Designate to consolidate all PRs submitted and prepare PO after using the applicable mode of procurement as indicated in the APP; and

36. d. The Municipal Accountant to strictly observe the procurement process and ensure that the forms are properly accomplished.

We recommended and the Management agreed to review the functions, systems and procedures, organizational structure, and staffing pattern of the Municipality to assess the needs and gaps, if any, and determine the appropriate human resource complement for the Municipality’s programs/ activities/projects in order to justify the need to hire JOs and to instruct the:

37. a. HRMO to prepare contract of services of the JOs which includes their specific job descriptions to be able to justify the need to hire Jos and as basis in measuring individual performance and submit copies to the Office of the Audit Team;

38. b. HRMO and Municipal Accountant to ensure that JOs prepare and submit accomplishment reports duly certified by immediate superior for the period being paid;

39. c. HRMO to facilitate the request for the procurement of new biometric system for the Municipality and require all employees and JOs to enroll in the biometric system and check that all DTRs were signed and approved to ensure reliability and compliance with the required number of hours of work; and

40. d. HRMO and Municipal Treasurer to adopt the use of Automated Teller Machine in the payment of wages of Job Order personnel in order to strengthen the internal control system in the Treasury Department; eliminate withdrawal of large sum of money for payroll purposes; reduce the workload and time spent by the Disbursing Officer in the preparation of pay envelopes.

We recommended the following measures to Management:
The Municipal Assessor, together with the personnel assigned by the Municipal Mayor, should exert utmost efforts to gather and/or prepare the documentary requirements needed to secure Transfer Certificates of Title (TCT) for all parcels of land acquired/owned in order to obtain primary evidence of ownership over said properties and safeguard government interests from third party claims, and ensure that all lots owned by the City have certificates of title and other proof of ownership;
The Municipal Accountant should review and verify the composition of the Land account to see to it that all parcels of land rightfully owned by the Municipality are recorded in the books of accounts to ensure fair presentation of the financial statements;
The Municipal Assessor and the Municipal Accountant should reconcile their records relative to the parcels of land or lots owned by the Municipal Government; and
Available funds allocated for the titling of parcels of lands should be utilized to facilitate titling of funds and not be used for other purposes.
During the exit conference, the Management has committed to comply with the audit recommendations.  It has also agreed to secure the TCTs for at least five properties which are covered by tax declarations in the name of the municipality.

To promote better control over inventories and reflect an accurate and more reliable balances of Inventory accounts in the Financial Statements, we recommended, and Management has agreed to:
Create an Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of unissued inventory items by type at least once a year and prepare the RPCI to be submitted to the Office of the Audit Team not later than January 31 of each year;
Instruct all Department Heads responsible for the custody of the inventory items to prepare RIS for all the issuances of inventories for proper monitoring and accountability and submit the same to the GSO-Designate;
Instruct the GSO-Designate to prepare the weekly SSMI based on the original RIS submitted by the various offices responsible in the custody of these inventories and submit the same to the City Accountant for proper recognition of supplies and materials expenses; and
Instruct the City Accountant and the GSO to maintain an updated Supplies Ledger Cards and stock cards, respectively, and undertake regular reconciliation between the two records.
Likewise, in order to facilitate compliance with the audit recommendations, Management committed to provide the GSO with additional manpower.

To promote better internal control over cash management and reflect a more reliable and correct balances in the Financial Statements, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Treasurer and/or concerned collecting officers to:
Stop the practice of issuing provisional receipts for collections received by the Municipality and require all the collecting officers to strictly use the appropriate accountable forms in acknowledging all kinds of collections.  Likewise, it is recommended that the accountable forms in the custody of the accountable officer assigned at PTA – San Fabian should be included in the preparation of the monthly CRAAF.
Ensure that all collecting officers issue the pre-numbered official receipts in strict chronological order and refrain from tampering or altering the original entries in the duplicate and triplicate copies of the ORs to ensure authenticity and reliability of the same.  In the event of errors, the OR should be cancelled and a new one shall be issued;
Ensure proper check and balance by performing cross-checking of reported collections with the amounts per ORs and ensure that cancelled ORs are correctly accounted for and reported on in the RCD;
Properly accomplish the RCDs in compliance with Section 49, Volume II of the MNGAS for LGUs;
See to it that allocated/assigned ORs for each type of fund is used/issued accordingly and consistently; and
Ensure that fidelity bonds are renewed on time and increase the fidelity bonds of accountable officers whose collections require greater accountability.
Management acknowledged the audit observations and recommendations and committed to strengthen the municipality’s internal controls on cash management in order to safeguard public funds.

We recommended the following measures to Management:
All Revenue Collection Clerks and/or authorized collecting officers should remit their collections intact to the Municipal Treasurer daily;
The Municipal Treasurer should ensure that all daily collections are deposited intact with the AGDB in compliance with the Section 69 (1) of PD 1445, Section 15 of the New Government Accounting System (NGAS) for Local Government Units (LGUs) and COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;
Management should coordinate with the AGDBs for possible arrangement for regular pick up of collections to facilitate the deposit of the same to the treasury account;
The Municipal Treasurer should immediately stop the practice of using cash collections to pay for disbursement transactions of the agency to avoid disallowance of cash items during conduct of cash examinations.
The Municipal Accountant, who serves as the Internal Auditor of the agency, should see to it that the aforementioned regulations are strictly complied with.
Management acknowledged and appreciated the Audit Team’s diligence in reviewing the municipality’s financial processes, particularly on cash management.
It was assured during the exit conference that an internal cleansing will be conducted to address the noted deficiencies.
It was also mentioned discussed during the exit conference that the full amount of ₱6,851,043.99 was already deposited.
A letter-reply to the Audit Observation Memorandum duly supported by copies of deposit slips was already submitted to the COA Office for validation/verification by the Audit Team.

We recommended, and the Management has agreed to instruct the Municipal Treasurer to:
Direct the concerned personnel to prepare and submit the CRAAF within the prescribed period;
Include all accountable forms with and without money value in the preparation of the CRAAF to ensure the completeness and reliability of the accountability reports in adherence with Section 86 of the Local Treasury Operations Manual (LTOM), 2nd Edition;
Require all collectors and/or accountable officers to prepare their respective RAAF at the close of each month and submit to the Municipal Treasurer for consolidation. Said RAAFs should be attached to the CRAAF; and
Ensure the accuracy of all data entries and completeness of vital information needed in the accountability reports.

We recommended the following measures to Management:
For the Municipal Treasurer to immediately stop the practice of utilizing the PCF for payment of AICS and other recurring expenses;
For the Municipal Treasurer to strictly utilize the PCF for payment of authorized non-recurring petty operating or miscellaneous expenses which cannot be conveniently paid through checks;
For the Municipal Mayor to designate a special disbursing officer from the Municipal Treasurer’s Office who will be responsible for drawing cash advances for the payment of AICS and subsequent liquidation thereof;
For the Municipal Mayor to consider undertaking a credit agreement with Petroleum companies relative to the consumption of fuel, oil and lubricants, subject however to the applicable rules and regulations under Republic Act No. 9184; and
For the Municipal Mayor to instruct the Municipal Accountant to record the cash advance for the payment of AICS under the account Advances to Special Disbursing Officer and Credit to Cash account.  Further, ensure that these cash advances are liquidated accordingly with complete supporting documents and through the use of Disbursement Vouchers (DVs) instead of Petty Cash Vouchers (PCVs).
During the exit conference, the Management has committed to comply with the audit recommendations.
As an initial action, a Special Disbursing Officer was immediately designated to take charge in the utilization and monitoring of the AICS.
Moreover, the Management informed the Audit Team that they have already entered into contracts with two oil companies to establish a credit line. This credit line will be utilized instead of using the PCF for payment of gasoline expenses.

We recommended and Management agreed that in order to maximize the effectiveness and efficiency of the GAD programs, activities and projects in addressing the significant gender issues and concerns, it will require the GAD Focal person to:

53. a) Establish and maintain operational GAD database that could either be manually operated or developed through software containing reliable and useful data;

54. b)  Conduct a gender analysis of their programs and projects through the administration of the Harmonized Gender and Development Guidelines (HGDG) tool. Likewise, to deepen their knowledge and build their competencies on GAD-related laws and international commitments, gender mainstreaming, gender analysis, gender responsive planning and budgeting and GAD-related tools among others;

55. c) Establish a GAD Monitoring and Evaluation System in order that outcomes of GAD programs, projects and activities be assessed and GAD areas that needs improvement will be properly identified and addressed.; and

56. d) Strictly observe the timelines in the preparation and submission of GAD Plan and Budget and GAD Accomplishment Report accompanied by the supporting documents as required by PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 and COA Circular 2014-001 dated March 18, 2014
.

We recommended the Management to instruct the:
Municipal Assessor’s Office to process the titling of all parcels of land owned by the Municipal Government, including the completion and submission of all the lacking documentary requirements to facilitate faster processing of transfer of ownership and titling under the name of the Municipal Government;
Municipal Assessor and Municipal Budget Officer to allocate sufficient funds for the processing of transfer of ownership in favor of the LGU;
Secretary of the Sanggunian to provide copies of SB Resolution duly signed by the majority of the members authorizing the Municipal Mayor to enter into Contract for the purchase of land by the Municipality;
Municipal Accountant and GSO Designate to maintain complete records, including copies of proof of ownership of all the real properties of the Municipality; and
Henceforth, refrain from purchasing real properties more than the appraised value set by the PAC to avoid disadvantageous transactions against the government.
3.14 The management committed to comply with the aforementioned audit recommendations.

4.8   We recommended the following to the Management:
Instruct the Disposal Committee to conduct inspection, inventory and appraisal of unserviceable properties derecognized and accomplish the required Inventory and Inspection Report with their description and other required information of the property;
Submit to COA the Inventory Report of Unserviceable Properties for the inspection and approval by the COA Regional Technical Evaluation Services (RTES);
Require the Accounting Department to prepare the necessary reversing entry to bring back the cost/book value of the properties derecognized and reclassify the same to “Other PPE” account and recognize any Impairment loss in case the carrying amount is lower than its Net Realizable Value/Appraised Value. Subsequently, the assets will be dropped from the books after these are sold or disposed; and
Henceforth, ensure that prior to derecognition of the cost of unserviceable property/ies, the procedures in the disposal thereof as provided for under Section 79 of PD 1445 and Section 5 of Executive Order No. 888. are followed.
4.9    The management committed to adhere with the audit recommendations.

11.12 We recommended that the Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to immediately submit to the Office of the Auditor the nine DVs to establish the validity, legality and propriety of the transactions;
To instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to cease from paying and issuing checks to suppliers or contractors without complete documentation;
Refrain from lending vouchers and documents to unauthorized personnel and observe properly the guidelines in the disbursement process;
Henceforth, submit regularly and completely all DVs and supporting documents to COA within the prescribed period to establish the validity, propriety and legality of the disbursements made by the LGU and to avoid penalty of the Revised Penal Code.
11.13 The Management admitted the observed deficiencies and is set to abide with the audit recommendations.

24.9  We recommended the Management:
To improve their revenue forecasting and their current collection system by considering past trends/experiences and the impact of events such as the pandemic;
Exert extra effort for the realization of their projected income over the years such as sending collection/demand letters and conducting ocular inspection of the business establishments;
Require the Municipal Treasurer and the Business Permits and Licensing Officer to have an updated master list of business establishments and require those who have no business permits to apply for the same and collect the the necessary regulatory fees and taxes, and
Assess and collect the correct fees, charges, business permits and taxes in accordance with the Revenue Code;
Management acknowledged the audit observation and recommendations.
